{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-ad08e08a85f9cea3", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# HuBERT: Self-Supervised Speech Representation Learning by Masked Prediction of Hidden Units\narXiv: 2106.07447\nAuthors: Wei-Ning Hsu, Benjamin Bolte, Yao-Hung Hubert Tsai, Kushal Lakhotia, Ruslan Salakhutdinov, Abdelrahman Mohamed\nYear: 2021 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Proposes the Hidden-Unit BERT (HuBERT) approach for self-supervised speech representation learning, which uses an offline clustering step to provide aligned target labels for a BERT-like masked prediction loss over continuous speech inputs.\n  2. Demonstrates that applying the prediction loss exclusively over masked regions forces the model to learn a combined acoustic and language model, making the approach resilient to the quality of the cluster assignments.\n  3. Introduces an iterative refinement procedure that significantly improves cluster assignment quality by applying k-means clustering to the learned latent representations from a previous HuBERT iteration.\n  4. Shows that utilizing cluster ensembles with different codebook sizes or product quantization provides complementary information and further enhances representation learning.\n  5. Achieves state-of-the-art or matching results compared to wav2vec 2.0 on Librispeech and Libri-light benchmarks across various fine-tuning subsets, with the 1B parameter X-Large model yielding up to 19% and 13% relative WER reductions on challenging evaluation subsets.\n\nTags: SSL, ASR, SSL/预测式-离散\n===\n# TASTE: Text-Aligned Speech Tokenization and Embedding for Spoken Language Modeling\narXiv: 2504.07053\nAuthors: Liang-Hsuan Tseng, Yi-Chang Chen, Kuan-Yi Lee, Da-Shan Shiu, Hung-yi Lee\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduces Text-Aligned Speech Tokenization and Embedding (TASTE), an end-to-end approach that aligns speech tokens with corresponding text transcriptions during the tokenization stage to bridge the modality gap.\n  2. Proposes a specialized cross-attention mechanism that uses text as queries and frozen ASR encoder representations as keys and values to dynamically aggregate speech into text-aligned tokens without explicit alignment.\n  3. Demonstrates that TASTE preserves essential paralinguistic information while dramatically reducing speech token sequence length and achieving high reconstruction quality at an extremely low bitrate.\n  4. Enables straightforward joint text-speech spoken language modeling via one-to-one text-speech token correspondence and Low-Rank Adaptation on pre-trained text LLMs.\n  5. Shows that the resulting spoken language model outperforms other pre-trained SLMs in speech continuation and likelihood-based tasks while preserving the text QA capabilities of its base LLM.\n  6. Presents the first end-to-end approach that utilizes a reconstruction objective to learn a joint tokenization and embedding tailored for text-speech spoken language modeling.\n\nTags: 压缩, LALM, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, LALM/音频标记-融合\n===", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "340d3a16-9213-410c-b0ca-9c61c43bc9ea", "uuid": "90af467e-46ee-40b6-9ade-3eecce578fab", "timestamp": "2026-07-22T08:20:44.682Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# HuBERT: Self-Supervised Speech Representation Learning by Masked Prediction of Hidden Units\narXiv: 2106.07447\nAuthors: Wei-Ning Hsu, Benjamin Bolte, Yao-Hung Hubert Tsai, Kushal Lakhotia, Ruslan Salakhutdinov, Abdelrahman Mohamed\nYear: 2021 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Proposes the Hidden-Unit BERT (HuBERT) approach for self-supervised speech representation learning, which uses an offline clustering step to provide aligned target labels for a BERT-like masked prediction loss over continuous speech inputs.\n  2. Demonstrates that applying the prediction loss exclusively over masked regions forces the model to learn a combined acoustic and language model, making the approach resilient to the quality of the cluster assignments.\n  3. Introduces an iterative refinement procedure that significantly improves cluster assignment quality by applying k-means clustering to the learned latent representations from a previous HuBERT iteration.\n  4. Shows that utilizing cluster ensembles with different codebook sizes or product quantization provides complementary information and further enhances representation learning.\n  5. Achieves state-of-the-art or matching results compared to wav2vec 2.0 on Librispeech and Libri-light benchmarks across various fine-tuning subsets, with the 1B parameter X-Large model yielding up to 19% and 13% relative WER reductions on challenging evaluation subsets.\n\nTags: SSL, ASR, SSL/预测式-离散\n===\n# TASTE: Text-Aligned Speech Tokenization and Embedding for Spoken Language Modeling\narXiv: 2504.07053\nAuthors: Liang-Hsuan Tseng, Yi-Chang Chen, Kuan-Yi Lee, Da-Shan Shiu, Hung-yi Lee\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduces Text-Aligned Speech Tokenization and Embedding (TASTE), an end-to-end approach that aligns speech tokens with corresponding text transcriptions during the tokenization stage to bridge the modality gap.\n  2. Proposes a specialized cross-attention mechanism that uses text as queries and frozen ASR encoder representations as keys and values to dynamically aggregate speech into text-aligned tokens without explicit alignment.\n  3. Demonstrates that TASTE preserves essential paralinguistic information while dramatically reducing speech token sequence length and achieving high reconstruction quality at an extremely low bitrate.\n  4. Enables straightforward joint text-speech spoken language modeling via one-to-one text-speech token correspondence and Low-Rank Adaptation on pre-trained text LLMs.\n  5. Shows that the resulting spoken language model outperforms other pre-trained SLMs in speech continuation and likelihood-based tasks while preserving the text QA capabilities of its base LLM.\n  6. Presents the first end-to-end approach that utilizes a reconstruction objective to learn a joint tokenization and embedding tailored for text-speech spoken language modeling.\n\nTags: 压缩, LALM, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, LALM/音频标记-融合\n===", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
